Nice — MNIST handwritten digit recognition is a perfect “capstone” because you can touch almost every requirement without the project becoming huge.
Here’s a clean way to map your course requirements onto one coherent project architecture (and what to build so it looks “advanced programming”-level, not just a notebook).
Project idea (one product, three UIs)
Handwritten Number Identifier with:
1.	Core ML package (training + inference)
2.	REST API (FastAPI) for predictions and model management
3.	Two frontends
o	PyQt5 desktop app (draw a digit, predict)
o	Streamlit web app (upload/draw, predict, view confidence)
4.	Database (SQLAlchemy) to store predictions, model versions, metrics, user inputs (optional), audit logs
________________________________________
How each course requirement fits (concretely)
1) Object orientation (classes, inheritance, composition)
•	ModelBase (abstract): predict(), load(), save()
•	TorchMnistModel(ModelBase) or SklearnMnistModel(ModelBase)
•	Preprocessor classes: ResizeNormalize, CenterCrop, Binarize (chainable)
•	Repository classes: PredictionRepository, ModelRepository
•	Service classes: PredictionService, TrainingService
2) Data parsing & validation (Pydantic)
Use Pydantic for:
•	PredictRequest (base64 image / bytes, optional metadata)
•	PredictResponse (digit, probabilities, model_version, latency_ms)
•	TrainRequest (hyperparams, epochs, batch_size)
•	ModelInfo (id, created_at, accuracy, path)
This is especially nice in FastAPI because it’s “native”.
3) Exception handling
Define custom exceptions:
•	InvalidImageError
•	ModelNotLoadedError
•	DatabaseError
•	TrainingFailedError
Then map them to:
•	HTTP error responses in FastAPI
•	GUI dialogs in PyQt5
•	Streamlit error boxes
4) System and file operations
•	Save models to models/ with versioned filenames
•	Log to logs/
•	Load configuration from .env / config.yaml
•	Export confusion matrix / metrics JSON
•	Optional: “import image from file” in PyQt5
5) Basic design patterns (MVC)
You can do MVC in both UIs:
PyQt5
•	Model: PredictionService
•	View: the widgets (canvas, buttons, labels)
•	Controller: handles events, calls service, updates UI
Streamlit
•	View is the page
•	Controller logic in functions
•	Model still PredictionService + API client
6) Desktop GUI: PyQt5
Features that feel “advanced”:
•	drawing canvas (QPainter)
•	brush size / clear button
•	live preview of the 28x28 preprocessed image
•	show top-3 probabilities
7) Web GUI: Streamlit
•	upload PNG/JPG or draw with a canvas component
•	show probabilities as bar chart
•	history of last N predictions (pulled from DB)
8) Database programming (SQLAlchemy)
Tables:
•	models (id, version, path, metrics, created_at)
•	predictions (id, timestamp, input_hash, predicted_digit, probs_json, model_id)
Optional:
•	feedback (if user corrects wrong prediction)
9) REST (FastAPI)
Endpoints:
•	POST /predict
•	POST /train (async/background job optional)
•	GET /models (list versions + metrics)
•	POST /models/{id}/activate
•	GET /health
10) AI-Enhanced development + critical review
